{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628829","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628829"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:01:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:01:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17240"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17240","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17240"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9930"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77887"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9930"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17240"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63372"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"10706"},{"type":"tags","id":"10960"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23282"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23287"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77887"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring protein synthesis, mutations in DNA can affect the final protein product. Understanding these mutations is crucial for diagnosing genetic disorders.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the consequence of a nonsense mutation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Deletes a single nucleotide causing frameshift","Creates a truncated protein due to premature stop codon","Inserts a single nucleotide causing frameshift","Substitutes one base for another without effect","Changes one amino acid to another amino acid"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Enonsense mutation creates a truncated protein due to a premature stop codon\u003C/strong\u003E. This typically results in a non-functional protein product that may be degraded by cellular quality control mechanisms like nonsense-mediated decay.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeletes a single nucleotide causing frameshift\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes a deletion mutation which alters the reading frame of the gene\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInserts a single nucleotide causing frameshift\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes an insertion mutation which alters the reading frame of the gene\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubstitutes one base for another without effect\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes a silent mutation that does not change the amino acid sequence\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChanges one amino acid to another amino acid\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes a missense mutation, not a nonsense mutation\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of premature stop codons can lead to various genetic disorders depending on the affected gene. The resulting truncated proteins are usually non-functional and may be rapidly degraded by cellular quality control mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Nonsense mutations create premature stop codons that result in truncated, usually non-functional proteins.","Nonsense-mediated decay is a cellular quality control mechanism that degrades mRNA containing premature stop codons.","Nonsense mutations are distinct from missense mutations which cause amino acid substitutions."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63372"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17240"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63372"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T20:19:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T20:20:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9930"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77887"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4940"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udee7","name":"Cell Biology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T13:16:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"14"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"met